Cinnamon

Cinnamomum verum

Culinary Herbs
Author: P. Kawatra
Published: 05/10/2015
Read Time: 5 minutes
Category: Culinary Herbs
Location: India

Description

Cinnamon (Cinnamomum verum), also known as Ceylon cinnamon, is a small evergreen tree or bushy shrub belonging to the laurel family (Lauraceae). It typically grows 8 to 15 meters tall in the wild but as a cultivated plant is often kept shorter by coppicing. The tree has thick, smooth bark from which the spice is derived by peeling the dried inner bark.

Overall, cinnamon is a fragrant, versatile medicinal and culinary herb with deep cultural and economic importance, especially in South Asia and Sri Lanka

Medicinal Properties

Antioxidant Anti-inflammatory Antimicrobial Antiviral Antidiabetic Blood sugar regulator Antiseptic Memory enhancer

Common Uses

  • 1)Blood sugar control in diabetes
  • 2)Relief from cold, flu, and cough
  • Antiseptic for minor Wounds
  • 3( anti-inflammatory for arthritis and joint pain
  • 4)Boosting digestion and appetite
  • Antimicrobial treatment for infections
  • 5(Cardiovascular health support
  • 6)Memory and brain health enhancement

Growing Information

Growing Conditions

Tropical climate, warm temperature, well-drained soil, slightly acidic to neutral pH (6.0-7.0), partial to full sunlight, high humidity, protection from strong wind, moderate fertilizer, organic-rich soil.

Water Requirements

Regular watering but avoid waterlogging; soil should be moist but well-drained.

Temperature Range

Optimal 20C to 30C; avoid temperatures below 15C.

Harvesting Tips

Harvest the cinnamon bark when the tree is 2-3 years old; the bark is peeled off from branches and dried properly. The best quality bark peels easily into thin curls.

Preparation Methods

Cinnamon bark can be dried and ground into powder for oral use or tea preparations. Essential oils or aqueous extracts can be prepared by soaking the bark powder in water or distillation for oil. A common method is boiling the bark in water to extract active compounds, then filtering to get a medicinal decoction.

Cinnamon medicinal preparations commonly involve extracting bioactive compounds using aqueous (water-based) methods, which are safe and environmentally friendly. A typical method includes grinding dried cinnamon bark into powder, then mixing it with sterile water, followed by heating (for example, at 70C for 1 hour). The mixture is then stirred, centrifuged to separate solid residues, filtered, and the resulting liquid extract can be lyophilized (freeze-dried) for storage or further use. This aqueous extract retains key compounds like cinnamaldehyde, cinnamic acid, and polyphenols responsible for medicinal effects such as anti-inflammatory and anticancer properties.Other preparation methods include:

Chemical Compounds

Cinnamaldehyde Eugenol Cinnamic acid Coumarin Cinnamyl acetate Borneol Polyphenols
